From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Hefesto DualSense4Unix Project <hefesto-dualsense4unix@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Tue, 21 Jul 2026 22:00:00 -0300
Subject: [PATCH] HID: nintendo: optionally register LEDs even when the
 initial set fails

On a bluetooth link degraded by 2.4GHz congestion (measured live with
four controllers connected: the initial player-LED set fails with
-ETIMEDOUT during probe), the driver skips LED class device
registration entirely ("Failed to set players LEDs, skipping
registration"). The controller then never gets player LEDs for its
whole connection lifetime, even after the link recovers seconds later:
userspace has no LED node to write to, so nothing can heal it short of
a full reconnect.

Registration itself is a local operation that cannot upset the
controller; only the initial SET went missing. Add a
register_leds_on_set_failure parameter (default N = historical
behavior): when set, the player and home LED class devices are
registered despite the failed initial set, and the next brightness
write from userspace (e.g. a player-slot assignment) heals the LEDs
over the recovered link.

Observed in the field on a Pro Controller (bus 0005): probe at boot
under congestion logged "Failed to set players LEDs, skipping
registration; ret=-110" followed by 13x "timeout waiting for input
report", leaving the controller permanently without player LEDs while
otherwise functional.

Signed-off-by: Hefesto DualSense4Unix Project <hefesto-dualsense4unix@users.noreply.github.com>
---
 drivers/hid/hid-nintendo.c | 19 +++++++++++++++----
 1 file changed, 15 insertions(+), 4 deletions(-)

index 4bfa968..b40c4b3 100644
--- a/drivers/hid/hid-nintendo.c
+++ b/drivers/hid/hid-nintendo.c
@@ -79,6 +79,11 @@ module_param(skip_tx_on_rate_exceeded, bool, 0644);
 MODULE_PARM_DESC(skip_tx_on_rate_exceeded,
 		 "Skip a subcommand/rumble transmission when no safe TX window was found instead of transmitting anyway (default N = transmit, same as before)");

+static bool register_leds_on_set_failure;
+module_param(register_leds_on_set_failure, bool, 0644);
+MODULE_PARM_DESC(register_leds_on_set_failure,
+		 "Register LED class devices even when the initial LED set fails (e.g. -ETIMEDOUT on a congested bluetooth link), so a later brightness write can heal the controller instead of leaving it without player LEDs forever (default N = skip registration, same as before)");
+
 /*
  * Reference the url below for the following HID report defines:
  * https://github.com/dekuNukem/Nintendo_Switch_Reverse_Engineering
@@ -2344,10 +2349,12 @@ static int joycon_leds_create(struct joycon_ctlr *ctlr)
 	mutex_lock(&ctlr->output_mutex);
 	ret = joycon_set_player_leds(ctlr, 0, led_val);
 	mutex_unlock(&ctlr->output_mutex);
-	if (ret) {
+	if (ret && !register_leds_on_set_failure) {
 		hid_warn(hdev, "Failed to set players LEDs, skipping registration; ret=%d\n", ret);
 		goto home_led;
 	}
+	if (ret)
+		hid_warn(hdev, "Failed to set players LEDs, registering anyway; ret=%d\n", ret);

 	for (i = 0; i < JC_NUM_LEDS; i++) {
 		led = &ctlr->leds[i];
@@ -2379,10 +2386,12 @@ home_led:
 		mutex_lock(&ctlr->output_mutex);
 		ret = joycon_set_home_led(ctlr, 0);
 		mutex_unlock(&ctlr->output_mutex);
-		if (ret) {
+		if (ret && !register_leds_on_set_failure) {
 			hid_warn(hdev, "Failed to set home LED, skipping registration; ret=%d\n", ret);
 			return 0;
 		}
+		if (ret)
+			hid_warn(hdev, "Failed to set home LED, registering anyway; ret=%d\n", ret);

 		ret = devm_led_classdev_register(&hdev->dev, led);
 		if (ret) {
--
